text:
About the EN's Law:
Let 'p' be the probability of a member having technical difficulties, and 'N' be the number of members in a collab. The probability of at least one having difficulties is 1 minus 'the probability of no one having any difficulties,' which is 1-(1-p)^N. When p is small enough than 1, (1-p)^N can be approximated to 1-Np, and 1-(1-p)^N becomes Np, which directly states the EN's Law. Calli's guess was actually mathematically correct!

text: She needs to tell them perks are arranged alphabetically(all hex perks start with H) for better searching. While mostly considering custom games where they have all perks available, I highly suggest better together, bond, deja vu, detective's hunch, visionary, wake up, and windows of opportunity. As new survivors, perks helping in finding gens, each other and escape paths are better than exhaustion/situational perks they won't optimize nor anti-tunneling perks they don't need since they already play nice with each other. For when they are the killer, I suggest bbq&chili, bloodhound, I'm all ears, infectious fright, lethal pursuer, shadowborn, spies from the shadows, tinkerer and zanshin tactics. These help with guiding you where you need to be, where you hunt, and where to avoid. I try to avoid suggesting perks that would make it too hard for both sides like hex perks as it can be overwhelming with too many things to find and worry about. Also, iron grasp+agitation would pretty much shutdown wiggling which can be fun as surv so it might be too much too. And if Kronii wants to use no mither(hopefully with tenacity), she can make a deal with the killer to let her get up maybe once or twice lol
author: @The17thNoah

text: ¬†@The17thNoah¬† spine chill is something i would suggest over windows of opportunity. Unless they know how to loop a killer, seeing all the pallets is not really that helpful as a newbie. At least it wasnt for me.
author: @randomperson-up5vt

text: ¬†@randomperson-up5vt¬† If the map is filled with short unsafe loops, yes hiding is better and spine chill is better. Generally tho, I argue the opposite. Windows of opportunity is literally only useful as a newbie when you have no idea about map layout or looping. While panicking in a chase, you can be guided where to run next and not just end up on dead zones or along the map walls lol. You also might not know it's been buffed to have no cooldown too. Spine chill only shows it's true potential when you know how to interpret it and not just run/hide whenever it lights up. Not to mention hiding properly also take skill and map awareness but if you have the affinity for it more than running then definitely go spine chill. Terror radius is often more than enough tho and they gotta give stealth killers a chance when they play them. Seeing them still get pulled from gens is hilarious. Honestly, I'm worried their surv stealth skills grow faster than their killer track skills. They've been quite silly losing track of people in front of them already. Getting used to chasing people in 1st person perspective will take time.
author: @The17thNoah

text:
¬†@The17thNoah¬† very good counter points. Still once you know how to  how to loop more reliably, seeing what pallets are still up can be useful. Since from mine and seeing others early game experience. Inexperienced players would waste them all the time because we are bad at looking behind or setting up a killer for a stun. I use the word waste because it's a finite resource that players only have so many of per map. 

So I still argue another way to know a killer is nearby can extend a survivors life expectancy. Especially since they are doing kill your friends mode. They have a much wider option of build variety.
author: @randomperson-up5vt

text: ¬†@randomperson-up5vt¬† Very good points too. I also hope they can enjoy a variety of builds and other situational perks once they get good enough to understand and use them.
author: @The17thNoah

text: ¬†@The17thNoah¬† I hope they do try out a lot of builds in the game as survivor and killers
